# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: diesel-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The **1970s energy crisis** occurred when the Western world, particularly the United States, Canada, Western Europe, Australia, and New Zealand, experienced substantial petroleum shortages as well as elevated prices.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The two worst crises of this period were the 1973 oil crisis and the 1979 oil crisis, when, respectively, the Yom Kippur War and the Iranian Revolution triggered interruptions in Middle Eastern oil exports.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The crisis began to unfold as petroleum production in the United States and some other parts of the world peaked in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] World oil production per capita began a long-term decline after 1979.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The oil crises prompted the first shift towards energy-saving (in particular, fossil fuel-saving) technologies.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The major industrial centers of the world were forced to contend with escalating issues related to petroleum supply.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Western countries relied on the resources of countries in the Middle East and other parts of the world.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The crisis led to stagnant economic growth in many countries as oil prices surged.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Although there were genuine concerns with supply, part of the run-up in prices resulted from the perception of a crisis.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The combination of stagnant growth and price inflation during this era led to the coinage of the term *stagflation*.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] By the 1980s, both the recessions of the 1970s and adjustments in local economies to become more efficient in petroleum usage, controlled demand sufficiently for petroleum prices worldwide to return to more sustainable levels.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The period was not uniformly negative for all economies.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Petroleum-rich countries in the Middle East benefited from increased prices and the slowing production in other areas of the world.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Some other countries, such as Norway, Mexico, and Venezuela, benefited as well.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] In the United States, Texas and Alaska, as well as some other oil-producing areas, experienced major economic booms due to soaring oil prices even as most of the rest of the nation struggled with the stagnant economy.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Many of these economic gains, however, came to a halt as prices stabilized and dropped in the 1980s.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East has existed since Israel's declaration of independence in 1948, including a number of wars.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1956 Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked when Israel's southern port of Eilat was blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to Anglo-French investors.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] One of the objectives of the Anglo-French-Israeli invasion was the removal of President Gamal Abdel Nasser who was aligning with the Soviet Union.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt's closure of the Suez Canal for eight years after Israel occupied the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975 after the 1973 Yom Kippur War, when Egypt tried and failed to take back the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel in the war after learning that the Soviet Union, was aiding Syria and Egypt in the war.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The real price of petroleum was stable in the 1970 timeframe, but there had been a sharp increase in American imports, putting a strain on American balance of trade, alongside other developed nations.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] During the 1960s, petroleum production in some of the world's top producers with extraction technology at the time began to peak.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] West Germany reached its production peak in 1966, Venezuela and the United States in 1970, and Iran in 1974.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Canada's conventional oil production peaked around the same time (though non-conventional production later helped revive Canadian production to some degree).
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The worldwide production per capita peaked soon afterward.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Although production in other parts of the world was increasing, the peaks in these regions began to put substantial upward pressure on world oil prices.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Equally as important, control of the oil supply became an increasingly important problem as countries like West Germany and the U.S. became increasingly dependent on foreign suppliers for this key resource.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973 oil crisis was a direct consequence of the U.S production peak in late 1960 and the beginning of 1971 (and shortages, especially for heating oil, started from there).
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The "embargo" as described below is the "practical name" given to the crisis.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] For the main Arab producers, the "embargo" supposedly allowed them to show to "the Arab street" that they were doing something to support Egypt in reclaiming its territory in Sinai and Gaza.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] In reality, it was more a desire to punish the U.S for re-supplying Israel with weapons during the Yom Kippur War, after the Soviet Union re-supplied Syria and Egypt with weapons.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] In real market terms (number of barrels) the embargo was almost a non-event, as it was only conducted by a few countries, against a few countries.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The embargo was never effective from Saudi Arabia towards the US, as reported by James E.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Akins in interview at 24:10 in the documentary "la face cachée du pétrole part 2".
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Akins, who audited US capacity for Nixon after US peak, was US ambassador in Saudi Arabia at that time.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Lawrence Rocks and Richard Runyon captured the unfolding of these events at the time in The Energy Crisis book.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] OAPEC declared it would limit or stop oil shipments to the United States and other countries if they supported Israel in the conflict.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] With the US actions seen as initiating the oil embargo, the long-term possibility of embargo-related high oil prices, disrupted supply and recession, created a strong rift within NATO; both European countries and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from the US Middle East policy.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Arab oil producers had also linked the end of the embargo with successful US efforts to create peace in the Middle East, which complicated the situation.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] To address these developments, the Nixon Administration began parallel negotiations with both Arab oil producers to end the embargo, and with Egypt, Syria, and Israel to arrange an Israeli pull back from the Sinai and the Golan Heights after the fighting stopped.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] By January 18, 1974, Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was sufficient to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] By May, Israel agreed to withdraw from parts of the Golan Heights close to the Syrian border.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Independently, the OPEC members agreed to use their leverage over the world price-setting mechanism for oil to stabilize their real incomes by raising world oil prices.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] This action followed several years of steep income declines after the recent failure of negotiations with the major Western oil companies earlier in the month.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] For the most part, industrialized economies relied on crude oil, and OPEC was a major supplier.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Because of the dramatic inflation experienced during this period, a popular economic theory has been that these price increases were to blame, as being suppressive of economic activity.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] However, the causality stated by this theory is often questioned.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The targeted countries responded with a wide variety of new, and mostly permanent, initiatives to contain their further dependency.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973 "oil price shock", along with the 1973–1974 stock market crash, have been regarded as the first event since the Great Depression to have a persistent economic effect.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] A crisis emerged in the United States in 1979 during the wake of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Amid massive protests, the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, fled his country in early 1979, allowing the Ayatollah Khomeini to gain control.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The protests shattered the Iranian oil sector.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] While the new regime resumed oil exports, it was inconsistent and at a lower volume, forcing prices to go up.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Saudi Arabia and other OPEC nations, under the presidency of Dr.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Mana Alotaiba increased production to offset the decline, and the overall loss in production was about 4 percent.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] However, a widespread panic resulted, driving the price far higher than would be expected under normal circumstances.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] In 1980, following the Iraqi invasion of Iran, oil production in Iran nearly stopped, and Iraq's oil production was severely cut as well.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Afterwards, oil prices began a decline as other countries began to fill the production shortfalls from Iran and Iraq.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973 and 1979 energy crisis had caused petroleum prices to peak in 1980 at over US$35 per barrel (US$137 in today's dollars).
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Following these events slowing industrial economies and stabilization of supply and demand caused prices to begin falling in the 1980s.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The glut began in the early 1980s as a result of slowed economic activity in industrial countries (due to the 1973 and 1979 energy crises) and the energy conservation spurred by high fuel prices.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The inflation adjusted real 2004 dollar value of oil fell from an average of $78.2 per barrel in 1981 to an average of $26.8 in 1986.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] This sentiment was echoed in November 1981, when the CEO of Exxon also characterized the glut as a temporary surplus, and that the word "glut" was an example of "our American penchant for exaggerated language".
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] He wrote that the main cause of the glut was declining consumption.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] In the United States, Europe and Japan, oil consumption had fallen 13% from 1979 to 1981, due to "in part, in reaction to the very large increases in oil prices by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and other oil exporters", continuing a trend begun during the 1973 price increases.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] After 1980, reduced demand and overproduction produced a glut on the world market, causing a six-year-long decline in oil prices culminating with a 46 percent price drop in 1986.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The U.S. reported negative economic growth during the 1970s and remained weak till the 1980s as the post World War II economic boom drew to a close.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Other causes that contributed to the recession included the Vietnam War, which turned out costly for the United States and the fall of the Bretton Woods system.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The emergence of newly industrialized countries rose competition in the metal industry, triggering a steel crisis, where industrial core areas in North America and Europe were forced to re-structure.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973–1974 stock market crash made the recession evident.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] According to the National Bureau of Economic Research, the U.S. economy slid into a recession in 1973–75.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Inflation levels remained high even when an economic expansion took place afterwards.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] During this recession, the Gross Domestic Product of the United States fell 3.2%.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Although the recession ended in March 1975, the unemployment rate did not peak for several months.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] In May 1975, the rate reached its height for the cycle of 9%.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The recession also lasted from 1973 to 1975 in the United Kingdom.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The GDP declined by 3.9% or 3.37% depending on the source.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] It took 14 quarters for the UK's GDP to recover to that at the start of recession.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] High oil prices in the 1970s induced investment in oil production by non-OPEC countries, particularly for reserves with a higher cost of production.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] These included Prudhoe Bay in Alaska, the North Sea offshore fields of the United Kingdom and Norway, the Cantarell offshore field of Mexico, and oil sands in Canada.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] As a result of the 1973 crisis many nations created strategic petroleum reserves (SPRs), crude oil inventories (or stockpiles) held by the governments of particular countries or private industry, for the purpose of providing economic and national security during an energy crisis.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The International Energy Agency (IEA) was formed in the wake of this crisis and currently comprises 31 member countries.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] According to the IEA, approximately 4.1 billion barrels (650,000,000 m3) of oil are held in strategic reserves by the member countries, of which 1.4 billion barrels (220,000,000 m3) is government-controlled.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The remainder is held by private industry.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] These reserves are intended to be equivalent to at least 90 days of net imports.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Strategic Petroleum Reserve is one of the largest government-owned reserves, with a capacity of up to 713.5 million barrels (113,440,000 m3).
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Recently, other non-IEA countries have begun creating their own strategic petroleum reserves, with China being the second largest overall and the largest non-IEA country.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Since Israel's declaration of independence in 1948 this state has found itself in nearly continual conflict with the Arab world and some other predominantly Muslim countries.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The animosity between the Arabs and the Israelis became a global issue during the 1970s.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The Yom Kippur War of 1973, with the supplying of Israel by its Western allies while some Arab states received Soviet supplies, made this one of the most internationally threatening confrontations of the period.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The large oil discoveries in the Middle East gave some Muslim countries unique leverage in the world, beginning in the 1960s.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973 and 1979 crises, in particular, were demonstrations of the new power that these countries had found.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The United States and other countries were forced to become more involved in the conflicts between these states and Israel.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] One of the first challenges OPEC faced in the 1970s was the United States' unilaterally pulling out of the Bretton Woods Accord and taking the U.S. off the established Gold Exchange Standard in 1971.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The change resulted in instability in world currencies and depreciation of the value of the U.S. dollar, as well as other currencies.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The revenues of OPEC also took a hit since they priced oil in dollars.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Finally OPEC started pricing oil against gold to combat the situation.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] But OPEC still struggled to maintain stability in the region as the negotiations between them and other Western oil companies bore little to no positive results.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] The major oil-producing regions of the U.S.—Texas, Oklahoma, Louisiana, Colorado, Wyoming, and Alaska—benefited greatly from the price inflation of the 1970s as did the U.S. oil industry in general.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Oil prices generally increased throughout the decade; between 1978 and 1980 the price of West Texas Intermediate crude oil increased 250 percent.
[src:diesel-engine/1970s-energy-crisis] Although all states felt the effects of the stock market crash and related national economic problems, the economic benefits of increased oil revenue in the Oil Patch states generally offset much of this.
[src:diesel-engine/2-2-car-body-style] A **2+2** (also **2-plus-2**) is a car-body style that has a seat each for the driver and front passenger, and two rear seats.
[src:diesel-engine/2-2-car-body-style] The latter may be individual "bucket" seats, fold-downs, or a full-width "bucketed" bench seat, but always with less leg room than either the front seats or a standard two-door car.
[src:diesel-engine/2-2-car-body-style] The style is different from four- or five-seat automobiles having normal-size rear seats, with second-row 2+2 seating typically only suitable for children or occasional use.
[src:diesel-engine/2-2-car-body-style] By standard definition, all cars in the 2+2 category have two front seats and two rear seats.
[src:diesel-engine/2-2-car-body-style] Other common characteristics for 2+2 cars include relatively little room for the rear passengers and a "streamlined" body with two doors.
[src:diesel-engine/2-2-car-body-style] While 2+2 seating is most commonly associated with coupés, especially those which strongly favour front passenger seating such as sports cars and grand tourer, certain convertibles with "auxiliary"-type rear seats may also be regarded as 2+2s.
[src:diesel-engine/2-2-car-body-style] Some vehicles (such as the TVR Cerbera and Toyota iQ) have been marketed as "3+1" due to their front passenger seat having more space for forward adjustment than the driver's, allowing for more leg room for one rear-seat passenger.
[src:diesel-engine/2-2-car-body-style] There are many coupés which meet the definition of a 2+2 but are not described by their manufacturers as such.
[src:diesel-engine/2-2-car-body-style] This is because the term *2+2* is most often used to distinguish cars with what typically amounts to auxiliary rear seating, at times enlarged from a two-seat version of the same model to accommodate it, such as the Jaguar E-type fixed-head coupé 2+2.
[src:diesel-engine/2-2-car-body-style] Other similar examples of stretched two-seaters include the Lotus Elan +2, Mazda RX-8, and Nissan 280ZX 2+2.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] The **2006 24 Hours of Le Mans** was the 74th Grand Prix of Endurance, and took place over 17–18 June 2006.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] The winners of the race were Frank Biela, Marco Werner, and Emanuele Pirro, driving the Audi R10 TDI.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] For the first time in the history of the race, the winner was a diesel-powered car.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] Prior to this race the ACO redeveloped the area around the Dunlop Curve and Dunlop Chicane, moving the Dunlop Curve in tighter to create more run-off area, while also turning the Dunlop Chicane into a larger set of turns.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] As part of the development, a new extended pit lane exit was created for motorcycles running the Bugatti Circuit.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] This second pit exit re-enters the track just beyond the Dunlop Chicane and before the Dunlop Bridge.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] Before the official test days, the FIA requested that the sportscars should also use this new pit lane, and mandated a 60 km/h speed limit for the entire 450m length, instead of using the normal pit exit in the Dunlop Curve as planned.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] This was originally used for the Le Mans test days, but due to complaints from the teams, the ACO decided to return to the old pit lane exit for the race.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the LMP1 category, during Wednesday's wet-weather qualifying Pescarolo C60 took the top two spots.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] Then, a day later, during dry weather conditions the new Audi R10 TDIs overtook the Pescarolos to claim the top two positions.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] Lola ran two seconds quicker than the new Intersport Lola.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] In LMGT1, the Aston Martin factory squad swept the front row, with the #64 Corvette right behind them.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] In GT2, the French IMSA Performance Matmut Porsche took the quickest time; however, Luca Riccitelli took the car off at *Nord du Karting* at the end of the session, injuring his ankle and badly damaging the chassis of the car.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] In a unique move, the ACO went against its own rules and granted permission for the team to replace the chassis with a brand new car.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] The car was still forced to start at the back of the grid.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Scuderia Ecosse Ferrari 430 thus started at the front for the GT2 class.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] Class leaders and the fastest lap time on each day are in **bold**.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] This race marked the first Le Mans win for a diesel engined sports car, the Audi R10 TDI, and the second time that a diesel-powered sports car won a major international motorsports event, following the Audi R10 TDI's win at the 2006 12 Hours of Sebring.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] This was, however, not the first time a diesel-powered racing car had won an international racing event; back in 1998, BMW became the first marque to enter a diesel-powered race winner as they won the Nürburgring 24 Hours with their 320d touring car.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] This race also marked the first time since 1991 that Porsche (or a Porsche-powered prototype) did not win a single class in Le Mans.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] A Panoz Esperante was successful in upsetting the contingent of Porsches in the GT2 class, the only class that did feature Porsche entries.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] Corvette Racing's 355-lap pace in their GT1 class win became the record for a homologated GT racer.
[src:diesel-engine/2006-24-hours-of-le-mans] Cars not completing 70% of the winner's distance are listed as Not Classified (NC).
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The **Nürburgring 24 Hours** is a 24-hour annual touring car and GT endurance racing event that takes place on a combination of the Nordschleife ("North Loop") and the GP-Strecke ("Grand Prix track") circuits of the Nürburgring in Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Held since 1970, the over 25.3 km (15.7 mi) lap length allows more than 200 cars and over 700 drivers to participate.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Starting in 2024, the event has been officially named **ADAC RAVENOL 24h Nürburgring** for sponsorship reasons.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Furthermore, the 2024 season of the race was included in the Intercontinental GT Challenge calendar.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Officially called "ADAC 24h Rennen Nürburgring" in German ('ADAC 24 hour Race Nürburgring'), it was introduced in 1970 by the ADAC as an official race, unlike the earlier endurance contests that covered 12, 24 (in 1961 and 1967), 36, 84 and even 96 hours, like the Marathon de la Route.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] This substitute for the Liège-Rome-Liège and Liège-Sofia-Liège rallies was held on the Nürburgring from 1965 to 1971.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] It is similar to the Spa 24 Hours, which had been introduced in 1924, following the 24 Hours of Le Mans.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The ADAC had held its first 1000 km Nürburgring sports car racing event in 1953.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] As the 1000 km Spa had been introduced in 1966, the 24h at the Ring gave both circuits a pair of endurance racing events at very long tracks, at least until Spa was shortened in 1979.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Just like the VLN series with its 4-hour races, the 24h race is mainly aimed at amateurs, in order to fill a starting field of around 200 cars.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Unlike the VLN races, the 24h is officially an international event, with trilingual (French, German and English, since 2024 because SRO regulations are in French) organization and documentation.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Entry fees are due, in 2010 these were €7,508 per car, of which €3,000 was an advance payment for fuel.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Typical entries range from second hand standard road cars to European Touring Car Championship vehicles and GT3 sports cars like the Porsche 911 GT3.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The participation of manufactures and professional teams and drivers has varied over the decades.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] As this section and its large paved run-off areas was useful as extra paddock zone for the competitors of the support races, it is bypassed with a sharp Z-shape chicane since 2005 for a 25.3 km (15.7 mi) track length.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The number of cars starting is limited to 150 as of 2024, driven by up to 600 drivers, as 2, 3 or 4 can share a car.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] One driver is allowed to drive 150 minutes non-stop, and can enter on two cars, yet a rest time of at least 2 hours has to be observed between two turns of the same driver.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The race is typically held in May or June on the Ascension Day or Corpus Christi holiday.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The 2020 race was postponed to September and held with limited spectators, restricted to the Grand Prix course area (initially planned to be held behind closed doors) due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The 2024 race set a new shortest distance record of just 50 laps with less than 10 hours of racing due to rain and overnight fog; the 2023 race set a new longest distance run for the race, as well as the first win for Ferrari.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The Nurburgring 24 Hours is known for its wide variety of cars.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] In 2023, 135 cars in 20 classes were entered.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The race has often seen cars that are rarely used in other international racing events.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Examples include Fiat Cinquecentos in the 1990s, a Volkswagen Caravelle in 2000, the P4/5 Competizione in the 2010s, or a 1988 Opel Manta that has raced from 1994 to 2023.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Due to the length of the track, the Nürburgring 24 Hours has unusual safety procedures compared to other modern professional endurance races.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Safety cars are not used except during red flag and ensuing restart situations, double yellow flags indicate a local speed limit of 120 km/h (75 mph), and code 60 flags, used locally for incidents warranting a safety car on shorter tracks, limit the speed to 60 km/h (37 mph).
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] It is common for course cars and vehicle recovery trucks to travel around the course under local double yellow flags.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Since 2015; competitors must hold a valid "DMSB Permit Nordschleife", a license to race specifically on the Nordschleife section of the Nürburgring.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] They must also take part in 3 races on the track within the last 2 calendar years.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Closing speeds between the fastest and slowest car classes is a common concern, as the track has many blind crests and corners.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] In 2023, a serious accident happened between a Porsche 911 GT3 R and a Dacia Logan SP3 - the slowest car in the field that year - after the Porsche hit the Logan at the high-speed Stefan-Bellof-S and sent it into the barriers.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The unpredictable Eifel weather is also a danger.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Heavy rain and fog stopped the race for several hours in 2018, 2020 and 2021, while the 2016 race was red-flagged due to an unusual hailstorm storm that caused a series of crashes.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] In 2001, driver Christian Peruzzi was killed after a practice accident in an Alfa Romeo 147.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The Nürburgring 24 Hours has several support races on Thursday, Friday and Saturday, some happening on the GP Track, some happening on the Nordschleife only, some happening on the combined track.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] As of 2023, the support program includes the Rundstrecken Challenge Nürburgring, and several historic touring cars and GT races.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The last support race is the ADAC 24h-Classic, a 3 hour race on the combined track on Saturday morning, several hours before the 24 Hours race.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Unlike the two previous races, held on Ascension Day weekend in May in rainy and very cold weather, the 2006 event was run in warm, sunny and dry conditions on Corpus Christi (feast) weekend of June 17–18.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Pure factory teams that challenged for the overall win were absent, yet Aston Martin and Maserati had entered factory-backed cars to promote their products, reminding of three overall wins each in the 1000 km Nürburgring decades ago.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The Aston Martin car with Aston CEO Ulrich Bez finished 4th in class and 24th overall.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Due to good conditions and stiff competition by similar cars, a new overall distance record (3,832 km (2,381 mi) in 151 laps) was scored by the Porsche 996 GT3 of Manthey Racing that already had been the best privateer team in the previous three years.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] This team is partially supported by Porsche, though, with factory drivers, a 3.8L 500 PS (370 kW; 490 hp) engine and a sequential gear box.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Second place finishers Jürgen Alzen/Uwe Alzen/Klaus Ludwig/Christian Abt of team *Jürgen Alzen Motorsport* was only one lap down and have beaten the old record, too.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] They used a conventional gear box and a privately built 3.8L 500PS engine.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The third of three fastest Porsche, the *Wolfgang Land Motorsport* 911, had suffered a fiery failure of its standard 3.6L Porsche 911 GT3-RSR race engine after 21 hours, yet was classified as 14th with 133 laps.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] A remarkable 5th place overall was scored by a BMW 120d from Schubert Motors, which had roughly half the power of some of the cars it beat.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] It was driven by Claudia Hürtgen (2005 VLN champion), Marc Hennerici (2005 privateer WTCC champion), Johannes Stuck (son of Hans-Joachim Stuck) and team owner Torsten Schubert.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] For the 2007 event held on Corpus Christi weekend of June 7–10, more than 260 teams had applied for the 220 race entries.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Prior to the start which had been scheduled for 15:00, an approaching thunderstorm made the organizers delay the beginning of the race.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Lightning struck the camp of fans, injuring several, while heavy rain made the track muddy.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] At 16:51, the race was started after two laps behind a safety car.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Veteran Klaus Ludwig at the wheel of the Aston Martin DBRS9 which had been given the number 007 took the lead in wet conditions, but hesitating too long with the change to dry tyres, the favorite Manthey team took the lead in their new Porsche 997 GT3-RSR.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] More weather-related drama occurred in the night, when the race was interrupted due to fog for six hours, making the race 18 hours.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] When the race resumed, the Land Porsche 996 GT3-RSR was slightly damaged when hitting the back of the Manthey car, and the Aston Martin engine failed.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Thus the Manthey team could easily defend its 2006 victory.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The reliable, yet no more fast enough Zakspeed Dodge Viper GTS-R came in second, with the Alzen brothers Porsche Cayman in 4th and the BMW Z4 M-Coupe 5th.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Remarkable performances were the top ten finishes of a VW Golf 5, an Opel Astra GTC and a BMW 130i, and the 13th place of a Hyundai Coupe V6 piloted by ex British Touring Car racer Peter Cate.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] For the 2008, over 270 cars were entered, of which only 230 could be accepted.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The race began in sunny weather with drama for the favorite Porsche teams of Manthey and Land, losing time with a leaky radiator and a tire failure, and the new Alzen 997 Turbo and the Zakspeed Viper battling for the lead.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] After the Viper was out, only the BMW Z4 (E85) of Claudia Hürtgen, pole setter and winner of the recent VLN race, could challenge the Porsche armada and lead for some laps, but it crashed during the night.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Manthey could catch up and win the race for a third time in a row, with the winning car of 2006 (a 996 model) finishing 2nd.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The triumph made the team mechanics cut off Olaf Manthey's famous moustache tips.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Sabine Schmitz came in third, also on a Porsche 997.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] A strong showing among the high powered cars gave the three new Volkswagen Scirocco, finishing 9th and 12th, with veteran Hans Joachim Stuck driving both cars.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] For 2009, the organizers announced that they wanted to reduce the gap in speeds, by not accepting small capacity cars any more, and by slowing down the fastest classes, SP7 and SP8.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Also, the new FIA GT3 and FIA GT4 classes were adopted, called SP9 and SP10.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Some of the new rules are controversial, especially the fact that instead of the regular fuel pumps as used in any public station, the top teams have to use expensive equipment designed to equal the times needed to refill, meaning that an economic car is punished compared to a thirsty car.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Due to the various rule changes, some teams have declined to take part, namely Zakspeed with their Viper.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Probably also due to the economic crisis, the number of entries was much lower than in previous years, with only 170 cars starting the race.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Surprisingly, the pole was set by a Ford GT, followed closely by the four factory-entered Audi R8 LMS and two Porsche GT3 of the Manthey team.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] They decided to enter their well-known RSR, which is basically a GT2 car, but now has about 70 hp less due to new air restrictors, and also a *997 GT3 Cup S*, the version Porsche homologated for FIA GT3.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] For the first 19 hours, two of the Audis and the two Manthey Porsche battled for the lead within a lap, the pace likely to result in a new distance record.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The Manthey #1 had been punished for approaching an accident site too quickly and had to wait 3 minutes in the box, but the decision was reverted later based on data logging evidence, with the lost time deducted from the results.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Around 11:30, the #99 Audi which had a narrow lead was stopped by suspension problems.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Following repairs this car finished in 5th position.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] This left the #97 Audi in second, and with the win in its class, 5 minutes behind the overall winner.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The 2010 event on Ascension Day weekend of May 13–16 saw a return of most prominent entries, except the Ford GT, as team Raeder had discontinued this project.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] To give teams time to rest or for repairs before the race, the night practice was scheduled on Thursday evening.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] In cold and wet conditions, the Farnbacher-entered Ferrari F430 GTC set the best lap time before the session was red-flagged due to fog.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] In Friday afternoon qualifying, held in fair weather, it crashed out and was barely repaired in time for the race.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Four of the five factory-backed Audi R8 LMS (officially entered by "customers", which happen to be the Audi-DTM-teams Phoenix Racing and Abt Sportsline) occupied the first four places on the grid, with Marco Werner setting pole at 8:24.753 with a new record average speed of 181 km/h (112 mph).
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] With lap times around 8:29, three of Porsche's new SP9/GT3-class cars occupied places 5 to 7, two of them entered by four-time winner Team Manthey, which had chosen to let the #1 car do only a single lap.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] BMW had entered two of their ALMS BMW M3 GT2, run by Schnitzer Motorsport.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Due to the modifications that include a transaxle gear box, they do not comply to the standard rules set of SP classes and their "Balance of Performance".
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Along with a factory-entered Porsche GT3 Hybrid, the M3s were classed as E1-XP entries (the E1-XP class was actually intended for experimental factory entries).
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The better BMW and the Hybrid posted times of 8:32 and 8:34 in qualifying.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Save for the 16th placed GT3-class Dodge Viper, only several other Porsche, Audi R8 and V8-powered BMW Z4 (E89) have qualified in the top 20, with times up to 8:47, which earns them a blue flash light that is supposed to facilitate passing of the approx.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Porsche test driver Walter Röhrl had intended to enter on a standard road legal Porsche 911 GT3 RS, but had to withdraw for health reasons from the team that comprises racers Roland Asch and Patrick Simon, plus journalists Horst von Saurma and Chris Harris.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The car, entered in cooperation with sport auto (Germany), is registered as S-GO 2400, and was driven from Weissach to Nürburg.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] It has qualified with 9:15, 42nd overall, and 9th among the 17 SP7 class entrants, only beaten by its race-prepped Porsche 997 siblings.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The race was started on Saturday 3 p.m. in sunny but cold weather.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Already on the Grand Prix track, the #1 Manthey Porsche driven by five-time winner Marcel Tiemann passed all Audis, taking the lead and pulling away about 100 m (330 ft) before catching up in lap 2 with the slowest cars of the third group, which were still in their first lap.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] After lap 3, three Porsche lead ahead of three Audi, a BMW M3 and the Hybrid-Porsche, which due to his larger range could take the lead after the others pitted.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The #1 Manthey Porsche led by a couple of minutes until got involved in a collision after seven hours.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] At halftime, the race is on pace to another distance record, with the Audi #99 leading by a small margin ahead of the Hybrid Porsche, the only remaining representative of his brand in the top 8, which used to be dominated by Porsche in recent years.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Places three to eight were occupied by three Audi R8, two BMW, and, rather surprisingly, on p 5 the Ferrari which had started in row 21.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The Porsches that occupy most places up to 15th were followed by the CNG-powered Volkswagen Scirocco GT24, the road-legal Porsche GT3 RS and a Nissan Z33.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] On Sunday morning, the #99 Audi needed a rear axle change, and with less than 5 hours to go, also the second place #2 Audi failed.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] This left the Hybrid Porsche in a one lap lead ahead of the #25 BMW GT2 with gearbox woes and the Ferrari, until also the Porsche stopped with less than two hours to go.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The BMW made it to the finish, giving Pedro Lamy a record-tying fifth win ahead of Ferrari and Audi.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The best Porsche, entered by Alzen, finished only sixth, six laps ahead of the Falken Nissan and the road legal GT3.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The SP4 class was won by 4 Argentinian drivers in the BMW 325i E92 Coupe of Motorsport Team Sorg Rennsport.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] This was the first victory for an Argentinian team at the Nürburgring 24 Hours race and the first Argentinian team to compete in the Nürburgring since Juan Manuel Fangio.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] With Corpus Christi weekend being rather late in 2011 on June 23–26, the 2011 event was held two weeks after the 2011 24 Hours of Le Mans.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The first five VLN races of 2011 were won by a factory-entered BMW, a GT3-class Mercedes SLS, a new Ferrari 458, the Hybrid Porsche GT3 and finally an Audi R8 LMS, so at least these five different brands were expected to challenge for the overall win in the 24 hours.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] In the first qualifying session, the Hankook-sponsored Farnbacher-Ferrari used soft tyres and was about 7 seconds faster than the competitors, lapping at an average speed of over 181 km/h, the fastest since 1983, when it was still run with prototype cars.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] This earned the team the pole position, but also an extra weight of 25 kg in the pre-race update of the ‘Balance of Performance’.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] After a few hours in changing weather conditions, the team retired the ‘R’ to focus on the ‘RSR’ which already had won three times since 2007.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Without any problems, it went on to win its fourth Nürburgring 24 Hours, with a new distance record of 156 laps.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Second place was taken by another GT2-spec car, the #1 factory BMW M3 GT which had won in 2010.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Five GT3 cars of Audi and Mercedes followed.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The SP8/GT2-class #2 Ferrari had run into early problems, but set the fastest race lap in the final hours, finishing 8th and James Glickenhaus’ P4/5 Competizione finished 39th, second in the E1-XP2.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] After 2010 Sorg Rennsport took the victory in class SP4 again.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Gianvito Rossi, Diego Romanini, Alfredo Varini and Alexander Rappold have been the only team in that class.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The 2012 event was the first to have a "Top 40" qualifying shootout for the 40 fastest cars on the starting grid, which took place on the Friday after the first 2 qualifying sessions.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The #3 Phoenix Racing Team won the race in an Audi R8 LMS.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The 2013 race saw Aston Martin's hydrogen powered car run the first ever zero-emissions lap of the circuit.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The race also saw the first ever win for a Mercedes.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The #9 Team Black Falcon won the race in a Mercedes-AMG GT3.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The 2014 race set a new record for the total distance driven during a Nürburgring 24-hour race with 4,035 km (159 laps) driven by the top two cars.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The #4 Phoenix Racing Team won the race in an Audi R8 LMS.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The #28 Audi Sport Team WRT won the race in an Audi R8 LMS.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The #4 AMG-Team Black Falcon won the race in a Mercedes-AMG GT3.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The #29 Audi Sport Team Land / Montaplast Land-Motorsport Team won the race in an Audi R8 LMS.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The #912 Manthey Racing Team won the race in a Porsche 911 GT3 R.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The #4 Phoenix Racing Team won the race in an Audi R8 LMS Evo.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Traditionally held in May, it was announced on March that the race will be postponed to September 24–27 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The event was initially planned to be held behind closed doors, but later a limited amount of spectators were admitted.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] Rowe Racing (BMW M6 GT3) won the event, the first for BMW in 10 years, although the race was interrupted for most of the night due to inclement weather.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The 2021 race was won by the Porsche-based Manthey Racing, who was forced to sit out the previous year's race due to COVID-19 concerns involving the team crew.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] A new record low of 58 laps (and less than ten hours of actual racing) was covered, as the race was once again interrupted for most of the night due to inclement weather.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The 50th anniversary 2022 race took place on 28–29 May 2022.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] A total of 159 laps were completed by the winning car #15 from Scherer Sport Team Phoenix.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The #30 Frikadelli Racing Team won the race in a Ferrari 296 GT3 completing a total of 162 laps.
[src:diesel-engine/24-hours-nürburgring] The race set a new distance record and also marks Ferrari's first ever Nürburgring 24 Hours victory.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The **4 VD 14,5/12-1 SRW** is an inline four-cylinder diesel engine produced by the VEB IFA Motorenwerke Nordhausen from 1967 to 1990.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The engine was one of the standard modular engines for agricultural and industrial use in the Comecon-countries.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] Approximately one million units were made.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The 4 VD 14,5/12-1 SRW is a water-cooled four-stroke diesel engine with four inline cylinders.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The Fuel is injected with a mechanical direct injection system.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The bore is 120 mm, the stroke is 145 mm, the displacement is 6560 cm3.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The standard version of the engine produces 92 kW and has a torque of 422 Nm.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The combustion chamber system (M-System) was licensed by MAN.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The engine was produced in the versions 4 VD 14,5/12-1 SRW and 4 VD 14,5/12-2 SRW, the later revision was built primary for the NVA.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] (4 cylinder, four-stroke-diesel, stroke 14.5 cm / bore 12 cm, version 1, inline, water-cooled).
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The crankcase is made of grey cast iron, both the crankshaft and the camshaft are supported in five bearings.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The center bearing of the crankshaft is an axial bearing.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The camshaft is driven by a connecting gear, which also drives the injection pump.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The housing of the crankshaft bearing contains the housing of the oil pump.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] Some versions of the engine are equipped with a speedometer gear assembly, which is connected to the injection pump drive.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The engine has a forged crankshaft, supported in changeable thin-wall bearing shells.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The journals of the crankshaft and the connecting rods are polished and induction hardened.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The counter-weights are screwed on the center and outer crank arms.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The flywheel is connected to the power take-off side of the engine with screws.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The gear drive side of the crankshaft is equipped with a gear, which drives the oil pump and the gear which drives the camshaft.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The connecting rods are forged and weight-balanced.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] While the small connecting rod bore has a bearing pressed into the bore, the crank-sided bore of the connecting rod has a thin-wall bearing.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] For lubrication and cooling of the connecting rods they have small oil-ducts.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] Oil is pressed in the ducts from a nozzle at the upper side of the connecting rod.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The piston journals are secured with two circlips and are bathed in oil.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] A heat resistant light-metal-alloy is used for the cast pistons.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The combustion chamber is integrated into the piston.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] For compression, the pistons have two piston rings which slots are cast into the piston.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The pistons are also equipped with an oil control ring.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The cylinder liners are made of centrifugally cast iron, two rubber rings seal the liners off from the crankcase.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The engine has two cast iron cylinder blocks with two cylinders; every block has a head, which makes two cylinder heads.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The camshaft is gear driven by the connecting gear as described earlier.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] Every cylinder head has four overhead valves, which are activated by tappets, pushrods and rocker arms.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The injection nozzles are connected to the cylinder heads with a flange.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The valve seats are made of a heat-resistant material and unlikely to be worn out.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The engine has a water cooling system with a centrifugal pump, which is driven from the crankshaft with a belt; it runs always.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] Starting at 80 °C the water is pumped into the water cooler, before this temperature level, it circulates in the engine block only to increase the engine temperature fast.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The engine fan runs always, except from later versions of the engine which have a fan with an electro-magnetic clutch, which is activated at 92 °C by a temperature sensor.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The oil pump in the crankshaft bearing housing creates oil pressure and pumps the oil from the oil sump through the engine.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] In the main oil flow a sieve filter cleans the oil, the secondary oil flow has a centrifugal oil filter.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] Some engine variants don't have a sieve filter but a paper filter instead.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The lubrication of the injection pump and the air compressor may either be attached to the main oil flow or be attached to a separate oil lubrication system.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] For oil cooling the engine has an involute heat exchanger or a shell and tube heat exchanger.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] Shell and tube heat exchangers are found mostly in engines for the IFA W50.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] Fuel is pumped from an inline injection pump to the injection nozzles.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The injection pump is a pump with a rotational speed controller, fuel filter and a pump clutch.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] Some engines have an injection timing device instead of the pump clutch.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The rotational speed controller is either an all-speed controller or an idle speed controller.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The speed controllers are driven by the camshaft of the injection pump.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The idle speed controller does affect the idle and redline speed only, while the all-speed controller affects every rotation speed.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] For fuel filtering a paper filter is used.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] Engines for vehicles are equipped with an air compressor, to supply compressed air for the brakes.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] It is an air-cooled single-cylinder air-compressor driven by a belt.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The air-intake is next to the engine intake manifold.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The crankcase is not divided, the crankshaft is forged and has two ball bearings.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The pushrod is housed in a needle bearing, the piston journal has a plain bearing pressed into the push rod bore.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The piston has two piston rings and one oil control ring.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] Lubrication is done by a dry sump lubrication system, the compressor valves are poppet valves.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The cold start system has a solenoid valve and a glow filament which are connected in series.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] When starting the engine, diesel fuel comes through the solenoid valve and gets heated at the glow filament, the diesel fuel evaporates.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] It gets ignited at the last glow filament.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The heat increases the temperature of the air from the intake manifold and makes it possible to start the engine unless the temperature level is not below −15 °C.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The engine is fitted with a starter motor, which is mounted on the crankcase at the exhaust side with securing clips.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] It is a 24 V direct current series-wound motor with a rated power of 4 kW.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The three-phase current alternator has an electronic control unit.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] It is mounted on the exhaust side of the engine and is driven by a belt from the crankshaft.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] The engine was produced in seven basic variants.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] No specific names were used, instead engines were categorized after their intended use.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] In the mid-1980s, a prototype of an Otto cycle engine based upon the 4 VD 14,5/12-1 SRW was made.
[src:diesel-engine/4-vd-14-5-12-1-srw] This engine, designated the 4 VOG 14,5/12 SRW, (4 cylinder, four-stroke, Otto, gas, stroke 14.5 cm, bore 12 cm, upright standing, in-line engine, water cooled) had spark ignition, a throttle valve, and was specifically designed for running on gaseous fuels such as biogas and methane.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] One description of the fair noted that the world, "then still mired in the malaise of the Great Depression, could glimpse a happier not-too-distant future, all driven by innovation in science and technology".
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Fair visitors saw the latest wonders in rail travel, automobiles, architecture and even cigarette-smoking robots.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] A Century of Progress was organized as an Illinois nonprofit corporation in January 1928 for the purpose of planning and hosting a World's Fair in Chicago in 1934.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] City officials designated three and a half miles of newly reclaimed land along the shore of Lake Michigan between 12th and 39th streets on the Near South Side for the fairgrounds.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Postmaster General James Farley at a four-hour ceremony at Soldier Field.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The fair's opening night began with a nod to the heavens.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Lights were automatically activated when the rays of the star Arcturus were detected.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The star was chosen as its light had started its journey at about the time of the previous Chicago world's fair—the World's Columbian Exposition—in 1893.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The rays were focused on photoelectric cells in a series of astronomical observatories and then transformed into electrical energy which was transmitted to Chicago.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The fair buildings were multi-colored, to create a "Rainbow City" as compared to the "White City" of Chicago's earlier World's Columbian Exposition.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The buildings generally followed Moderne architecture in contrast to the neoclassical themes used at the 1893 fair.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] One famous feature of the fair were the performances of fan dancer Sally Rand.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Hal Pearl then known as "Chicago's Youngest Organist" and later "The King of the Organ" was the official organist of the fair.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Mary Ann McArdle and her sister Isabel (from the UK) performed Irish Dancing.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Other popular exhibits were the various auto manufacturers, the Midway (filled with nightclubs such as the Old Morocco, where future stars Judy Garland, the Cook Family Singers, and the Andrews Sisters performed), and a recreation of important scenes from Chicago's history.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The fair also contained exhibits that may seem shocking to modern audiences, including offensive portrayals of African Americans, a "Midget City" complete with "sixty Lilliputians", and an exhibition of incubators containing real babies.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The fair included an exhibit on the history of Chicago.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] In the planning stages, several African American groups from the city's newly growing population campaigned for Jean Baptiste Point du Sable to be honored at the fair.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] At the time, few Chicagoans had even heard of Point du Sable, and the fair's organizers presented the 1803 construction of Fort Dearborn as the city's historical beginning.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The campaign was successful, and a replica of Point du Sable's cabin was presented as part of the "background of the history of Chicago".
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Also on display was the "Lincoln Group" of reconstructions of buildings associated with the biography of Abraham Lincoln, including his birth cabin, the Lincoln-Berry General Store, the Chicago Wigwam (in reduced scale), and the Rutledge Tavern which served as a restaurant.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Admiral Byrd's polar expedition ship the *City of New York* was visited by President Franklin D.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Roosevelt when he came to the fair on October 2, 1933.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The *City* was on show for the full length of the exhibition.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] One of the highlights of the 1933 World's Fair was the arrival of the German airship *Graf Zeppelin* on October 26, 1933.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] After circling Lake Michigan near the exposition for two hours, Commander Hugo Eckener landed the 776-foot airship at the nearby Curtiss-Wright Airport in Glenview.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] It remained on the ground for twenty-five minutes (from 1 to 1:25 pm) then took off ahead of an approaching weather front, bound for Akron, Ohio.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] An enduring exhibit was the 1933 Homes of Tomorrow Exhibition that demonstrated modern home convenience and creative practical new building materials and techniques with twelve model homes sponsored by several corporations affiliated with home decor and construction.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Marine artist Hilda Goldblatt Gorenstein painted twelve murals for the Navy's exhibit in the Federal Building for the fair.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The frieze was composed of twelve murals depicting the influence of sea power on America, beginning with the settlement of Jamestown, Virginia, in 1607 when sea power first reached America and carrying through World War I.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Another set of murals, painted for the Ohio State Exhibit by William Mark Young, was relocated afterwards to the Ohio Statehouse.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Young also painted scenes of the exhibition buildings.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The first Major League Baseball All-Star Game was held at Comiskey Park (home of the Chicago White Sox) in conjunction with the fair.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] To cap its record-breaking speed run, the *Zephyr* arrived dramatically on-stage at the fair's "Wings of a Century" transportation pageant.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The two trains launched an era of industrial streamlining.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Both trains later went into successful revenue service, the Union Pacific's as the *City of Salina*, and the Burlington *Zephyr* as the first *Pioneer Zephyr*.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The *Zephyr* is now on exhibit at Chicago's Museum of Science and Industry.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Frank Buck furnished a wild animal exhibit, Frank Buck's Jungle Camp.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Over two million people visited Buck's reproduction of the camp he and his native assistants lived in while collecting animals in Asia.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] After the fair closed, Buck moved the camp to a compound he had created at Amityville, New York.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Planning for the design of the Exposition began over five years prior to Opening Day.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] According to an official resolution, decisions regarding the site layout and the architectural style of the exposition were relegated to an architectural commission, which was led by Paul Cret and Raymond Hood.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Local architects on the committee included Edward Bennett, John Holabird, and Hubert Burnham.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Frank Lloyd Wright was specifically left off the commission due to his inability to work well with others, but did go on to produce three conceptual schemes for the fair.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Members of this committee ended up designing most of the large, thematic exhibition pavilions.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Because the fairgrounds was on new man-made land that was owned by the state and not the city, the land was initially free from Chicago's strict building codes, which allowed the architects to explore new materials and building techniques.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Root) where fan dancer Sally Rand performed.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] These buildings were constructed out of five-ply Douglas fir plywood, ribbed-metal siding, and prefabricated boards such as Masonite, Sheetrock, Maizewood, as well as other new man-made materials.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The exhibited buildings were windowless (but cheerfully lighted) buildings.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Structural advances also filled the fairgrounds.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] From June to November 1933, there was an outbreak of amoebic dysentery associated with the fair.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] There were more than a thousand cases, resulting in 98 deaths.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Joel Connolly of the Chicago Bureau of Sanitary Engineering brought the outbreak to an end when he found that defective plumbing permitted sewage to contaminate drinking water in two hotels.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Originally, the fair was scheduled only to run until November 12, 1933, but it was so successful that it was opened again to run from May 26 to October 31, 1934.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The fair was financed through the sale of memberships, which allowed purchases of a certain number of admissions once the park was open.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] More than $800,000 (equal to $19,253,731 today) was raised in this manner as the country was in the Great Depression.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] A $10 million bond was issued on October 28, 1929, the day before the stock market crashed.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] By the time the fair closed in 1933, half of these notes had been retired, with the entire debt paid by the time the fair closed in 1934.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] For the first time in American history, an international fair had paid for itself.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] In its two years, it had attracted 48,769,227 visitors.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] According to James Truslow Adams's *Dictionary of American History*, during the 170 days beginning May 27, 1933, there were 22,565,859 paid admissions; during the 163 days beginning May 26, 1934, there were 16,486,377; a total of 39,052,236.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Much of the fair site is now home to Northerly Island park (since the closing of Meigs Field) and McCormick Place.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The Balbo Monument, given to Chicago by Benito Mussolini to honor General Italo Balbo's 1933 trans-Atlantic flight, still stands near Soldier Field.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The city added a third red star to its flag in 1933 to commemorate the Century of Progress Exposition (the Fair is now represented by the fourth of four stars on the flag).
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] In conjunction with the fair, Chicago's Italian-American community raised funds and donated a statue of Genoese navigator and explorer Christopher Columbus.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] It was placed at the south end of Grant Park, near the site of the fair.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The Polish Museum of America possesses the painting of *Pulaski at Savannah* by Stanisław Kaczor-Batowski, which was exhibited at the Century of Progress fair and where it won first place.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] After the close of the fair, the painting went on display at The Art Institute of Chicago where it was unveiled by Eleanor Roosevelt on July 10, 1934.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The painting was on display at the Art Institute until its purchase by the Polish Women's Alliance on the museum's behalf.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Post Office Department issued a special fifty-cent Air Mail postage stamp, (Scott catalogue number C-18) to commemorate the visit of the German airship depicting *(l to r)* the fair's Federal Building, the *Graf Zeppelin* in flight, and its home hangar in Friedrichshafen, Germany.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] This stamp is informally known as the *Baby Zep* to distinguish it from the much more valuable 1930 Graf Zeppelin stamps (C13–15).
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Separate from this issue, for the Fair the Post Office also printed 1 and 3 cent commemorative postage stamps, showing respectively Fort Dearborn and the modernistic Federal Building.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] These were also printed in separate souvenir sheets as blocks of 25 (catalog listings 728–31).
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] In 1935 the sheets were reprinted (Scott 766–67).
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] From October 2010 through September 2011, the National Building Museum in Washington, D.C. opened an exhibition titled *Designing Tomorrow: America's World's Fairs of the 1930s*.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] This exhibition prominently featured the Century of Progress fair in Chicago.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The major archive for the Century of Progress International Exposition, including the official records from the event and the papers of Lenox Lohr, general manager of the fair, are housed in Special Collections at the University of Illinois, Chicago.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] A collection of materials including images is held by the Ryerson & Burnham Libraries at the Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] The Century of Progress Collection includes photographs, guidebooks, brochures, maps, architectural drawings, and souvenir items.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Specific collections with material include the Chicago Architects Oral History Project; the Daniel H.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Burnham Jr. and Hubert Burnham Papers; Edward H.
[src:diesel-engine/a-century-of-progress] Bennett Collection; Voorhees, Gmelin, and Walker photographs.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] The **A-segment** is the first category in the passenger car classification system defined by the European Commission.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] It is used for **city cars**, the smallest category of passenger cars defined.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] A-segment sales represented approximately 4.2% of the European market in 2024.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] It is approximately equivalent to the kei car class in Japan.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] As of 2021, the A-segment category size spans from approximately 2.7 metres (110 in) to 3.7 metres (150 in).
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] Body styles for A-segment cars in Europe have historically nearly always been hatchbacks.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] But as crossovers gain popularity, new models have begun to shift to resemble crossovers.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] Examples of crossover city cars include Suzuki Ignis and Toyota Aygo X.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] Other body styles such as sedans have only a few models present in this segment because these shapes largely prove impractical at typical A-segment dimensions.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] A-segment cars are traditionally offered with manual transmission as the sole transmission option.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] Beginning in the 2010s, automatic options are increasingly available.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] Some newer models most often utilize CVTs, while a small number of manufacturers also offer automated manual transmissions.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] The engines of A-segment cars commonly range from 1.0 to 1.4 litres, either in inline-four or three configuration.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] Newer models may have turbocharged and/or hybrid engines with a particular emphasis on higher fuel efficiency.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] In 2020 the ten highest selling A-segment cars in Europe were Fiat Panda, Fiat 500, Toyota Aygo, Renault Twingo, Volkswagen Up!, Hyundai i10, Kia Picanto, Peugeot 108, Citroën C1 and Suzuki Ignis.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] 2019 - In 2019, sales of minicars were down 2% compared to a total market gain of 1% which means this segment now makes up 7.7% of the total European car market at 1.21 million sales, down from 8% in 2018.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] And with margins on minicars under pressure due to increased costs to comply with stricter safety and emissions standards, manufacturers are scaling back investments in to minicars or switching to an EV-only strategy.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] In Italy, A-segment cars represented 16.4% of car sales in the first half of 2019.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] 2020 - European sales of minicars were down by a third in 2020, which translates to nearly 400,000 fewer sales and means the segment loses market share as the overall market is down 24%.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] As a result, this segment now makes up 6.8% of the total European car market, down from 7.7% last year.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] And their share is expected to shrink further in coming years, as manufacturers are pulling out of this segment or switching their models to EV-only.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] This is a result of increasing costs to comply with stricter safety and especially emissions standards, which makes minicars nearly unprofitable, especially considering that for most models from European brands this is the only market.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] In the United States, minicar segment cars represented 0.5% of the market share.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] In 2020 the highest selling minicar segment cars in the U.S. were the Chevrolet Spark, Mitsubishi Mirage and Mini Cooper.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] In India, historically the A-segment cars had the highest sales.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] Sales have been in decline in recent years, falling from 70,000 sales per month in 2014 to 47,000 sales per month in 2016.
[src:diesel-engine/a-segment] As of 2019, several A-segment cars had successes outside Europe, such as Hyundai Grand i10, Honda Brio, Kia Picanto, Tata Tiago, Toyota Wigo, Suzuki Celerio, Suzuki Wagon R, Suzuki/Maruti Alto, Ford Figo, Smart ForTwo, Citroën C1, Peugeot 108, and modern Fiat 500.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] A **diesel engine** is an internal combustion engine in which ignition of diesel fuel is caused by the elevated temperature of the air in the cylinder due to mechanical compression; thus, the diesel engine is also called a **compression-ignition engine** (or **CI engine**).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] This contrasts with engines using spark plug-ignition of the air-fuel mixture, such as a petrol engine (gasoline engine) or a gas engine (using a gaseous fuel like natural gas or liquefied petroleum gas).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The diesel engine is named after its inventor, German engineer Rudolf Diesel.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel engines work by compressing only air, or air combined with residual combustion gases from the exhaust (known as exhaust gas recirculation, "EGR").
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Air is inducted into the chamber during the intake stroke, and compressed during the compression stroke.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] This increases air temperature inside the cylinder so that atomised diesel fuel injected into the combustion chamber ignites.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The torque a diesel engine produces is controlled by manipulating the air-fuel ratio (λ); instead of throttling the intake air, the diesel engine relies on altering the amount of fuel that is injected, and thus the air-fuel ratio is usually high.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The diesel engine has the highest thermal efficiency *(see engine efficiency)* of any practical internal or external combustion engine due to its very high expansion ratio and inherent lean burn, which enables heat dissipation by excess air.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] A small efficiency loss is also avoided compared with non-direct-injection gasoline engines, as unburned fuel is not present during valve overlap, and therefore no fuel goes directly from the intake/injection to the exhaust.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Low-speed diesel engines (as used in ships and other applications where overall engine weight is relatively unimportant) can reach effective efficiencies of up to 55%.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The combined cycle gas turbine (Brayton and Rankine cycle) is a combustion engine that is more efficient than a diesel engine, but due to its mass and dimensions, is unsuitable for many vehicles, including aircraft and some watercraft.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The world's largest diesel engines put in service are 14-cylinder, two-stroke marine diesel engines; they produce a peak power of almost 100 MW each.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel engines may be designed with either two-stroke or four-stroke combustion cycles.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] They were originally used as a more efficient replacement for stationary steam engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Since the 1910s, they have been used in submarines and ships.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Use in locomotives, buses, trucks, heavy equipment, agricultural equipment and electricity generation plants followed later.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] In the 1930s, they slowly began to be used in some automobiles.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Since the 1970s energy crisis, demand for higher fuel efficiency has resulted in most major automakers, at some point, offering diesel-powered models, even in very small cars.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] According to Konrad Reif (2012), the EU average for diesel cars at the time accounted for half of newly registered cars.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] However, air pollution and overall emissions are more difficult to control in diesel engines compared to gasoline engines, so the use of diesel engines in the US is now largely relegated to larger on-road and off-road vehicles.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Though aviation has traditionally avoided using diesel engines, aircraft diesel engines have become increasingly available in the 21st century.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] In 1878, Rudolf Diesel, who was a student at the "Polytechnikum" in Munich, attended the lectures of Carl von Linde.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Linde explained that steam engines are capable of converting just 6–10% of the heat energy into work, but that the Carnot cycle allows conversion of much more of the heat energy into work by means of isothermal change in condition.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] According to Diesel, this ignited the idea of creating a highly efficient engine that could work on the Carnot cycle.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel was also introduced to a fire piston, a traditional fire starter using rapid adiabatic compression principles which Linde had acquired from Southeast Asia.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] After several years of working on his ideas, Diesel published them in 1893 in the essay *Theory and Construction of a Rational Heat Motor*.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel was heavily criticised for his essay, but only a few found the mistake that he made; his *rational heat motor* was supposed to utilise a constant temperature cycle (with isothermal compression) that would require a much higher level of compression than that needed for compression ignition.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel's idea was to compress the air so tightly that the temperature of the air would exceed that of combustion.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] However, such an engine could never perform any usable work.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] By June 1893, Diesel had realised his original cycle would not work, and he adopted the constant pressure cycle.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel describes the cycle in his 1895 patent application.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Notice that there is no longer a mention of compression temperatures exceeding the temperature of combustion.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Now it is simply stated that the compression must be sufficient to trigger ignition.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] In 1892, Diesel received patents in Germany, Switzerland, the United Kingdom, and the United States for "Method of and Apparatus for Converting Heat into Work".
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] In 1894 and 1895, he filed patents and addenda in various countries for his engine; the first patents were issued in Spain (No.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel was attacked and criticised over several years.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Critics claimed that Diesel never invented a new motor and that the invention of the diesel engine is fraud.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Otto Köhler and Emil Capitaine were two of the most prominent critics of Diesel's time.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Köhler had published an essay in 1887, in which he describes an engine similar to the engine Diesel describes in his 1893 essay.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Köhler figured that such an engine could not perform any work.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Emil Capitaine had built a petroleum engine with glow-tube ignition in the early 1890s; he claimed against his own better judgement that his glow-tube ignition engine worked the same way Diesel's engine did.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] His claims were unfounded and he lost a patent lawsuit against Diesel.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Other engines, such as the Akroyd engine and the Brayton engine, also use an operating cycle that is different from the diesel engine cycle.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Friedrich Sass says that the diesel engine is Diesel's "very own work" and that any "Diesel myth" is "falsification of history".
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel sought out firms and factories that would build his engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] With the help of Moritz Schröter and Max Gutermuth, he succeeded in convincing both Krupp in Essen and the Maschinenfabrik Augsburg.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Contracts were signed in April 1893, and in early summer 1893, Diesel's first prototype engine was built in Augsburg.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] On 10 August 1893, the first ignition took place, the fuel used was petrol.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] In winter 1893/1894, Diesel redesigned the existing engine, and by 18 January 1894, his mechanics had converted it into the second prototype.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] During January that year, an air-blast injection system was added to the engine's cylinder head and tested.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Friedrich Sass argues that, it can be presumed that Diesel copied the concept of air-blast injection from George B.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Brayton, albeit that Diesel substantially improved the system.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] On 17 February 1894, the redesigned engine ran for 88 revolutions – one minute; with this news, Maschinenfabrik Augsburg's stock rose by 30%, indicative of the tremendous anticipated demands for a more efficient engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] On 26 June 1895, the engine achieved an effective efficiency of 16.6% and had a fuel consumption of 519 g·kW−1·h−1.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] However, despite proving the concept, the engine caused problems, and Diesel could not achieve any substantial progress.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Therefore, Krupp considered rescinding the contract they had made with Diesel.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel was forced to improve the design of his engine and rushed to construct a third prototype engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Between 8 November and 20 December 1895, the second prototype had successfully covered over 111 hours on the test bench.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] In the January 1896 report, this was considered a success.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] In February 1896, Diesel considered supercharging the third prototype.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Imanuel Lauster, who was ordered to draw the third prototype "Motor 250/400", had finished the drawings by 30 April 1896.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] During summer that year the engine was built, it was completed on 6 October 1896.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] First public tests began on 1 February 1897.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Moritz Schröter's test on 17 February 1897 was the main test of Diesel's engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The engine was rated 13.1 kW with a specific fuel consumption of 324 g·kW−1·h−1, resulting in an effective efficiency of 26.2%.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] By 1898, Diesel had become a millionaire.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The diesel internal combustion engine differs from the gasoline powered Otto cycle by using highly compressed hot air to ignite the fuel rather than using a spark plug (*compression ignition* rather than *spark ignition*).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] In the diesel engine, only air is initially introduced into the combustion chamber.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The air is then compressed with a compression ratio typically between 15:1 and 23:1.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] This high compression causes the temperature of the air to rise.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] At about the top of the compression stroke, fuel is injected directly into the compressed air in the combustion chamber.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] This may be into a (typically toroidal) void in the top of the piston or a *pre-chamber* depending upon the design of the engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The fuel injector ensures that the fuel is broken down into small droplets, and that the fuel is distributed evenly.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The heat of the compressed air vaporises fuel from the surface of the droplets.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The vapour is then ignited by the heat from the compressed air in the combustion chamber, the droplets continue to vaporise from their surfaces and burn, getting smaller, until all the fuel in the droplets has been burnt.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Combustion occurs at a substantially constant pressure during the initial part of the power stroke.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The start of vaporisation causes a delay before ignition and the characteristic diesel knocking sound as the vapour reaches ignition temperature and causes an abrupt increase in pressure above the piston (not shown on the P-V indicator diagram).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] When combustion is complete the combustion gases expand as the piston descends further; the high pressure in the cylinder drives the piston downward, supplying power to the crankshaft.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] As well as the high level of compression allowing combustion to take place without a separate ignition system, a high compression ratio greatly increases the engine's efficiency.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Increasing the compression ratio in a spark-ignition engine where fuel and air are mixed before entry to the cylinder is limited by the need to prevent pre-ignition, which would cause engine damage.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Since only air is compressed in a diesel engine, and fuel is not introduced into the cylinder until shortly before top dead centre (TDC), premature detonation is not a problem and compression ratios are much higher.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The pressure–volume diagram (pV) diagram is a simplified and idealised representation of the events involved in a diesel engine cycle, arranged to illustrate the similarity with a Carnot cycle.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Starting at 1, the piston is at bottom dead centre and both valves are closed at the start of the compression stroke; the cylinder contains air at atmospheric pressure.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Between 1 and 2 the air is compressed adiabatically – that is without heat transfer to or from the environment – by the rising piston.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] (This is only approximately true since there will be some heat exchange with the cylinder walls.) During this compression, the volume is reduced, the pressure and temperature both rise.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] At or slightly before 2 (TDC) fuel is injected and burns in the compressed hot air.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Chemical energy is released and this constitutes an injection of thermal energy (heat) into the compressed gas.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Combustion and heating occur between 2 and 3.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] In this interval the pressure remains constant since the piston descends, and the volume increases; the temperature rises as a consequence of the energy of combustion.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] At 3 fuel injection and combustion are complete, and the cylinder contains gas at a higher temperature than at 2.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Between 3 and 4 this hot gas expands, again approximately adiabatically.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Work is done on the system to which the engine is connected.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] During this expansion phase the volume of the gas rises, and its temperature and pressure both fall.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] At 4 the exhaust valve opens, and the pressure falls abruptly to atmospheric (approximately).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] This is unresisted expansion and no useful work is done by it.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] After the opening of the exhaust valve, the exhaust stroke follows, but this (and the following induction stroke) are not shown on the diagram.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] If shown, they would be represented by a low-pressure loop at the bottom of the diagram.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] At 1 it is assumed that the exhaust and induction strokes have been completed, and the cylinder is again filled with air.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The piston-cylinder system absorbs energy between 1 and 2 – this is the work needed to compress the air in the cylinder, and is provided by mechanical kinetic energy stored in the flywheel of the engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Work output is done by the piston-cylinder combination between 2 and 4.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The difference between these two increments of work is the indicated work output per cycle, and is represented by the area enclosed by the pV loop.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The adiabatic expansion is in a higher pressure range than that of the compression because the gas in the cylinder is hotter during expansion than during compression.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] It is for this reason that the loop has a finite area, and the net output of work during a cycle is positive.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The fuel efficiency of diesel engines is better than most other types of combustion engines, due to their high compression ratio, high air–fuel equivalence ratio (λ), and the lack of intake air restrictions (i.e. throttle valves).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Theoretically, the highest possible efficiency for a diesel engine is 75%.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] However, in practice the efficiency is much lower, with efficiencies of up to 43% for passenger car engines, up to 45% for large truck and bus engines, and up to 55% for large two-stroke marine engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The average efficiency over a motor vehicle driving cycle is lower than the diesel engine's peak efficiency (for example, a 37% average efficiency for an engine with a peak efficiency of 44%).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] That is because the fuel efficiency of a diesel engine drops at lower loads, however, it does not drop quite as fast as the Otto (spark ignition) engine's.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel engines are combustion engines and, therefore, emit combustion products in their exhaust gas.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Due to incomplete combustion, diesel engine exhaust gases include carbon monoxide, hydrocarbons, particulate matter, and nitrogen oxides pollutants.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] About 90 per cent of the pollutants can be removed from the exhaust gas using exhaust gas treatment technology.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Road vehicle diesel engines have no sulfur dioxide emissions, because motor vehicle diesel fuel has been sulfur-free since 2003.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Helmut Tschöke argues that particulate matter emitted from motor vehicles has negative impacts on human health.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The particulate matter in diesel exhaust emissions is sometimes classified as a carcinogen or "probable carcinogen" and is known to increase the risk of heart and respiratory diseases.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] In principle, a diesel engine does not require any sort of electrical system.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] However, most modern diesel engines are equipped with an electrical fuel pump, and an electronic engine control unit.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] However, there is no high-voltage electrical ignition system present in a diesel engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] This eliminates a source of radio frequency emissions (which can interfere with navigation and communication equipment), which is why only diesel-powered vehicles are allowed in some parts of the American National Radio Quiet Zone.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] To control the torque output at any given time (i.e. when the driver of a car adjusts the accelerator pedal), a governor adjusts the amount of fuel injected into the engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Mechanical governors have been used in the past, however electronic governors are more common on modern engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Mechanical governors are usually driven by the engine's accessory belt or a gear-drive system and use a combination of springs and weights to control fuel delivery relative to both load and speed.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Electronically governed engines use an electronic control unit (ECU) or electronic control module (ECM) to control the fuel delivery.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The ECM/ECU uses various sensors (such as engine speed signal, intake manifold pressure and fuel temperature) to determine the amount of fuel injected into the engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Due to the amount of air being constant (for a given RPM) while the amount of fuel varies, very high ("lean") air-fuel ratios are used in situations where minimal torque output is required.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] This differs from a petrol engine, where a throttle is used to also reduce the amount of intake air as part of regulating the engine's torque output.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Controlling the timing of the start of injection of fuel into the cylinder is similar to controlling the ignition timing in a petrol engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] It is therefore a key factor in controlling the power output, fuel consumption and exhaust emissions.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] There are several different ways of categorising diesel engines, as outlined in the following sections.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] High-speed engines are used to power trucks (lorries), buses, tractors, cars, yachts, compressors, pumps and small electrical generators.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] As of 2018, most high-speed engines have direct injection.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Many modern engines, particularly in on-highway applications, have common rail direct injection.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] On bigger ships, high-speed diesel engines are often used for powering electric generators.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The highest power output of high-speed diesel engines is approximately 5 MW.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Medium-speed engines are used in large electrical generators, railway diesel locomotives, ship propulsion and mechanical drive applications such as large compressors or pumps.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Medium speed diesel engines operate on either diesel fuel or heavy fuel oil by direct injection in the same manner as low-speed engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Usually, they are four-stroke engines with trunk pistons; a notable exception being the EMD 567, 645, and 710 engines, which are all two-stroke.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The power output of medium-speed diesel engines can be as high as 21,870 kW, with the effective efficiency being around 47-48% (1982).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Most larger medium-speed engines are started with compressed air direct on pistons, using an air distributor, as opposed to a pneumatic starting motor acting on the flywheel, which tends to be used for smaller engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Medium-speed engines intended for marine applications are usually used to power (ro-ro) ferries, passenger ships or small freight ships.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Using medium-speed engines reduces the cost of smaller ships and increases their transport capacity.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] In addition to that, a single ship can use two smaller engines instead of one big engine, which increases the ship's safety.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Low-speed diesel engines are usually very large in size and mostly used to power ships.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] There are two different types of low-speed engines that are commonly used: Two-stroke engines with a crosshead, and four-stroke engines with a regular trunk-piston.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Two-stroke engines have a limited rotational frequency and their charge exchange is more difficult, which means that they are usually bigger than four-stroke engines and used to directly power a ship's propeller.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Four-stroke engines on ships are usually used to power an electric generator.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Both types are usually very undersquare, meaning the bore is smaller than the stroke.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Low-speed diesel engines (as used in ships and other applications where overall engine weight is relatively unimportant) often have an effective efficiency of up to 55%.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Like medium-speed engines, low-speed engines are started with compressed air, and they use heavy oil as their primary fuel.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Four-stroke engines use the combustion cycle described earlier.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Most smaller diesels, for vehicular use, for instance, typically use the four-stroke cycle.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] This is due to several factors, such as the two-stroke design's narrow powerband which is not particularly suitable for automotive use and the necessity for complicated and expensive built-in lubrication systems and scavenging measures.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The cost effectiveness (and proportion of added weight) of these technologies has less of an impact on larger, more expensive engines, while engines intended for shipping or stationary use can be run at a single speed for long periods.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Two-stroke engines use a combustion cycle which is completed in two strokes instead of four strokes.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Filling the cylinder with air and compressing it takes place in one stroke, and the power and exhaust strokes are combined.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The compression in a two-stroke diesel engine is similar to the compression that takes place in a four-stroke diesel engine: As the piston passes through bottom centre and starts upward, compression commences, culminating in fuel injection and ignition.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Instead of a full set of valves, two-stroke diesel engines have simple intake ports, and exhaust ports (or exhaust valves).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] When the piston approaches bottom dead centre, both the intake and the exhaust ports are "open", which means that there is atmospheric pressure inside the cylinder.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Therefore, some sort of pump is required to blow the air into the cylinder and the combustion gasses into the exhaust.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The pressure required is approximately 10-30 kPa.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Due to the lack of discrete exhaust and intake strokes, all two-stroke diesel engines use a scavenge blower or some form of compressor to charge the cylinders with air and assist in scavenging.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Roots-type superchargers were used for ship engines until the mid-1950s, however since 1955 they have been widely replaced by turbochargers.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Usually, a two-stroke ship diesel engine has a single-stage turbocharger with a turbine that has an axial inflow and a radial outflow.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Crossflow scavenging is incomplete and limits the stroke, yet some manufacturers used it.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Reverse flow scavenging is a very simple way of scavenging, and it was popular amongst manufacturers until the early 1980s.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Uniflow scavenging is more complicated to make but allows the highest fuel efficiency; since the early 1980s, manufacturers such as MAN and Sulzer have switched to this system.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] It is standard for modern marine two-stroke diesel engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] So-called dual-fuel diesel engines or gas diesel engines burn two different types of fuel *simultaneously*, for instance, a gaseous fuel and diesel engine fuel.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The diesel engine fuel auto-ignites due to compression ignition, and then ignites the gaseous fuel.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Such engines do not require any type of spark ignition and operate similar to regular diesel engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The fuel is injected at high pressure into either the combustion chamber, "swirl chamber" or "pre-chamber," unlike petrol engines where the fuel is often added in the inlet manifold or carburetor.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Engines where the fuel is injected into the main combustion chamber are called direct injection (DI) engines, while those which use a swirl chamber or pre-chamber are called indirect injection (IDI) engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Most direct injection diesel engines have a combustion cup in the top of the piston where the fuel is sprayed.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Many different methods of injection can be used.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Usually, an engine with helix-controlled mechanic direct injection has either an inline or a distributor injection pump.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] For each engine cylinder, the corresponding plunger in the fuel pump measures out the correct amount of fuel and determines the timing of each injection.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] These engines use injectors that are very precise spring-loaded valves that open and close at a specific fuel pressure.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Separate high-pressure fuel lines connect the fuel pump with each cylinder.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Fuel volume for each single combustion is controlled by a slanted groove in the plunger which rotates only a few degrees releasing the pressure and is controlled by a mechanical governor, consisting of weights rotating at engine speed constrained by springs and a lever.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The injectors are held open by the fuel pressure.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] On high-speed engines the plunger pumps are together in one unit.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The length of fuel lines from the pump to each injector is normally the same for each cylinder in order to obtain the same pressure delay.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Direct injected diesel engines usually use orifice-type fuel injectors.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Electronic control of the fuel injection transformed the direct injection engine by allowing much greater control over the combustion.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Common rail (CR) direct injection systems do not have the fuel metering, pressure-raising and delivery functions in a single unit, as in the case of a Bosch distributor-type pump, for example.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The requirements of each cylinder injector are supplied from this common high pressure reservoir of fuel.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] An Electronic Diesel Control (EDC) controls both rail pressure and injections depending on engine operating conditions.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The injectors of older CR systems have solenoid-driven plungers for lifting the injection needle, whilst newer CR injectors use plungers driven by piezoelectric actuators that have less moving mass and therefore allow even more injections in a very short period of time.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Early common rail system were controlled by mechanical means.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The injection pressure of modern CR systems ranges from 140 MPa to 270 MPa.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] An indirect diesel injection system (IDI) engine delivers fuel into a small chamber called a swirl chamber, precombustion chamber, pre chamber or ante-chamber, which is connected to the cylinder by a narrow air passage.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Generally the goal of the pre chamber is to create increased turbulence for better air / fuel mixing.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] This system also allows for a smoother, quieter running engine, and because fuel mixing is assisted by turbulence, injector pressures can be lower.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Most IDI systems use a single orifice injector.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The pre-chamber has the disadvantage of lowering efficiency due to increased heat loss to the engine's cooling system, restricting the combustion burn, thus reducing the efficiency by 5–10%.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] IDI engines are also more difficult to start and usually require the use of glow plugs.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] IDI engines may be cheaper to build but generally require a higher compression ratio than the DI counterpart.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] IDI also makes it easier to produce smooth, quieter running engines with a simple mechanical injection system since exact injection timing is not as critical.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Most modern automotive engines are DI which have the benefits of greater efficiency and easier starting; however, IDI engines can still be found in the many ATV and small diesel applications.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Indirect injected diesel engines use pintle-type fuel injectors.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Early diesel engines injected fuel with the assistance of compressed air, which atomised the fuel and forced it into the engine through a nozzle (a similar principle to an aerosol spray).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] The nozzle opening was closed by a pin valve actuated by the camshaft.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Although the engine was also required to drive an air compressor used for air-blast injection, the efficiency was nonetheless better than other combustion engines of the time.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] However the system was heavy and it was slow to react to changing torque demands, making it unsuitable for road vehicles.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] A *unit injector* system, also known as "Pumpe-Düse" (*pump-nozzle* in German) combines the injector and fuel pump into a single component, which is positioned above each cylinder.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] This eliminates the high-pressure fuel lines and achieves a more consistent injection.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Under full load, the injection pressure can reach up to 220 MPa.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Unit injectors are operated by a cam and the quantity of fuel injected is controlled either mechanically (by a rack or lever) or electronically.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p01] Due to increased performance requirements, unit injectors have been largely replaced by common rail injection systems.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The average diesel engine has a poorer power-to-mass ratio than an equivalent petrol engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The lower engine speeds (RPM) of typical diesel engines results in a lower power output.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Also, the mass of a diesel engine is typically higher, since the higher operating pressure inside the combustion chamber increases the internal forces, which requires stronger (and therefore heavier) parts to withstand these forces.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The distinctive noise of a diesel engine, particularly at idling speeds, is sometimes called "diesel clatter".
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] This noise is largely caused by the sudden ignition of the diesel fuel when injected into the combustion chamber, which causes a pressure wave that sounds like knocking.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Engine designers can reduce diesel clatter through: indirect injection; pilot or pre-injection; injection timing; injection rate; compression ratio; turbo boost; and exhaust gas recirculation (EGR).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Common rail diesel injection systems permit multiple injection events as an aid to noise reduction.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Through measures such as these, diesel clatter noise is greatly reduced in modern engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel fuels with a higher cetane rating are more likely to ignite and hence reduce diesel clatter.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In warmer climates, diesel engines do not require any starting aid (aside from the starter motor).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] However, many diesel engines include some form of preheating for the combustion chamber, to assist starting in cold conditions.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Engines with a displacement of less than 1 litre per cylinder usually have glowplugs, whilst larger heavy-duty engines have flame-start systems.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The minimum starting temperature that allows starting without pre-heating is 40 °C (104 °F) for precombustion chamber engines, 20 °C (68 °F) for swirl chamber engines, and 0 °C (32 °F) for direct injected engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In the past, a wider variety of cold-start methods were used.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Some engines, such as Detroit Diesel engines used a system to introduce small amounts of ether into the inlet manifold to start combustion.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Instead of glowplugs, some diesel engines are equipped with starting aid systems that change valve timing.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The simplest way this can be done is with a decompression lever.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Activating the decompression lever locks the outlet valves in a slight down position, resulting in the engine not having any compression and thus allowing for turning the crankshaft over with significantly less resistance.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] When the crankshaft reaches a higher speed, flipping the decompression lever back into its normal position will abruptly re-activate the outlet valves, resulting in compression − the flywheel's mass moment of inertia then starts the engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Other diesel engines, such as the precombustion chamber engine XII Jv 170/240 made by Ganz & Co., have a valve timing changing system that is operated by adjusting the inlet valve camshaft, moving it into a slight "late" position.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] This will make the inlet valves open with a delay, forcing the inlet air to heat up when entering the combustion chamber.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Forced induction, especially turbocharging is commonly used on diesel engines because it greatly increases efficiency and torque output.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines are well suited for forced induction setups due to their operating principle which is characterised by wide ignition limits and the absence of fuel during the compression stroke.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Therefore, knocking, pre-ignition or detonation cannot occur, and a lean mixture caused by excess supercharging air inside the combustion chamber does not negatively affect combustion.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines can combust a huge variety of fuels, including several fuel oils that have advantages over fuels such as petrol.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In diesel engines, a mechanical injector system atomizes the fuel directly into the combustion chamber (as opposed to a Venturi jet in a carburetor, or a fuel injector in a manifold injection system atomizing fuel into the intake manifold or intake runners as in a petrol engine).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Because only air is inducted into the cylinder in a diesel engine, the compression ratio can be much higher as there is no risk of pre-ignition provided the injection process is accurately timed.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] This means that cylinder temperatures are much higher in a diesel engine than a petrol engine, allowing less volatile fuels to be used.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Therefore, diesel engines can operate on a huge variety of different fuels.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In general, fuel for diesel engines should have a proper viscosity, so that the injection pump can pump the fuel to the injection nozzles without causing damage to itself or corrosion of the fuel line.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] At injection, the fuel should form a good fuel spray, and it should not have a coking effect upon the injection nozzles.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] To ensure proper engine starting and smooth operation, the fuel should be willing to ignite and hence not cause a high ignition delay, (this means that the fuel should have a high cetane number).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel fuel should also have a high lower heating value.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Inline mechanical injector pumps generally tolerate poor-quality or bio-fuels better than distributor-type pumps.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Also, indirect injection engines generally run more satisfactorily on fuels with a high ignition delay (for instance, petrol) than direct injection engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Direct-injected engines with an MAN centre sphere combustion chamber rely on fuel condensing on the combustion chamber walls.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The fuel starts vaporising only after ignition sets in, and it burns relatively smoothly.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Therefore, such engines also tolerate fuels with poor ignition delay characteristics, and, in general, they can operate on petrol rated 86 RON.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In his 1893 work *Theory and Construction of a Rational Heat Motor*, Rudolf Diesel considers using coal dust as fuel for the diesel engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] However, Diesel just *considered* using coal dust (as well as liquid fuels and gas); his actual engine was designed to operate on petroleum, which was soon replaced with regular petrol and kerosene for further testing purposes, as petroleum proved to be too viscous.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In addition to kerosene and petrol, Diesel's engine could also operate on ligroin.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Before diesel engine fuel was standardised, fuels such as petrol, kerosene, gas oil, vegetable oil and mineral oil, as well as mixtures of these fuels, were used.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The first diesel fuel standards were the DIN 51601, VTL 9140-001, and NATO F 54, which appeared after World War II.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The modern European EN 590 diesel fuel standard was established in May 1993; the modern version of the NATO F 54 standard is mostly identical with it.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The DIN 51628 biodiesel standard was rendered obsolete by the 2009 version of the EN 590; FAME biodiesel conforms to the EN 14214 standard.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Watercraft diesel engines usually operate on diesel engine fuel that conforms to the ISO 8217 standard (Bunker C).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Also, some diesel engines can operate on gasses (such as LNG).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] DIN 51601 diesel fuel was prone to *waxing* or *gelling* in cold weather; both are terms for the solidification of diesel oil into a partially crystalline state.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The crystals build up in the fuel system (especially in fuel filters), eventually starving the engine of fuel and causing it to stop running.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Low-output electric heaters in fuel tanks and around fuel lines were used to solve this problem.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Also, most engines have a *spill return* system, by which any excess fuel from the injector pump and injectors is returned to the fuel tank.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Once the engine has warmed, returning warm fuel prevents waxing in the tank.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Before direct injection diesel engines, some manufacturers, such as BMW, recommended mixing up to 30% petrol in with the diesel by fuelling diesel cars with petrol to prevent the fuel from gelling when the temperatures dropped below −15 °C.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel fuel is less flammable than petrol, because its flash point is 55 °C, leading to a lower risk of fire caused by fuel in a vehicle equipped with a diesel engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel fuel can create an explosive air/vapour mix under the right conditions.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] However, compared with petrol, it is less prone due to its lower vapour pressure, which is an indication of evaporation rate.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The Material Safety Data Sheet for ultra-low sulfur diesel fuel indicates a vapour explosion hazard for diesel fuel indoors, outdoors, or in sewers.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel exhaust has been classified as an IARC Group 1 carcinogen.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] It causes lung cancer and is associated with an increased risk for bladder cancer.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The characteristics of diesel have different advantages for different applications.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines have long been popular in bigger cars and have been used in smaller cars such as superminis in Europe since the 1980s.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] They were popular in larger cars earlier, as the weight and cost penalties were less noticeable.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Smooth operation as well as high low-end torque are deemed important for passenger cars and small commercial vehicles.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The introduction of electronically controlled fuel injection significantly improved the smooth torque generation, and starting in the early 1990s, car manufacturers began offering their high-end luxury vehicles with diesel engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Passenger car diesel engines usually have between three and twelve cylinders, and a displacement ranging from 0.8 to 6.0 litres.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Modern powerplants are usually turbocharged and have direct injection.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines do not suffer from intake-air throttling, resulting in very low fuel consumption especially at low partial load (for instance: driving at city speeds).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] One fifth of all passenger cars worldwide have diesel engines, with many of them being in Europe, where approximately 47% of all passenger cars are diesel-powered.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Daimler-Benz in conjunction with Robert Bosch GmbH produced diesel-powered passenger cars starting in 1936.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The popularity of diesel-powered passenger cars in markets such as India, South Korea and Japan is increasing (as of 2018).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In 1893, Rudolf Diesel suggested that the diesel engine could possibly power "wagons" (lorries).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The first lorries with diesel engines were brought to market in 1924.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Modern diesel engines for lorries have to be both extremely reliable and very fuel efficient.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Common-rail direct injection, turbocharging and four valves per cylinder are standard.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Displacements range from 4.5 to 15.5 litres, with power-to-mass ratios of 2.5–3.5 kg·kW−1 for heavy duty and 2.0–3.0 kg·kW−1 for medium duty engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] V6 and V8 engines used to be common, due to the relatively low engine mass the V configuration provides.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Recently, the V configuration has been abandoned in favour of straight engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] These engines are usually straight-6 for heavy and medium duties and straight-4 for medium duty.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Their undersquare design causes lower overall piston speeds which results in increased lifespan of up to 1,200,000 kilometres (750,000 mi).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Compared with 1970s diesel engines, the expected lifespan of modern lorry diesel engines has more than doubled.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines for locomotives are built for continuous operation between refuelings and may need to be designed to use poor quality fuel in some circumstances.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Some locomotives use two-stroke diesel engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines have replaced steam engines on all non-electrified railroads in the world.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The first diesel locomotives appeared in 1913, and diesel multiple units soon after.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Nearly all modern diesel locomotives are more correctly known as diesel–electric locomotives because they use an electric transmission: the diesel engine drives an electric generator which powers electric traction motors.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] While electric locomotives have replaced the diesel locomotive for passenger services in many areas diesel traction is widely used for cargo-hauling freight trains and on tracks where electrification is not economically viable.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In the 1940s, road vehicle diesel engines with power outputs of 150–200 metric horsepower (110–150 kW; 150–200 hp) were considered reasonable for DMUs.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Commonly, regular truck powerplants were used.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The height of these engines had to be less than 1 metre (3 ft 3 in) to allow underfloor installation.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Usually, the engine was mated with a pneumatically operated mechanical gearbox, due to the low size, mass, and production costs of this design.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Some DMUs used hydraulic torque converters instead.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel–electric transmission was not suitable for such small engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In the 1930s, the Deutsche Reichsbahn standardised its first DMU engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] It was a 30.3 litres (1,850 cu in), 12-cylinder boxer unit, producing 275 metric horsepower (202 kW; 271 hp).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Several German manufacturers produced engines according to this standard.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The requirements for marine diesel engines vary, depending on the application.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] For military use and medium-size boats, medium-speed four-stroke diesel engines are most suitable.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] These engines usually have up to 24 cylinders and come with power outputs in the one-digit Megawatt region.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Small boats may use lorry diesel engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Large ships use extremely efficient, low-speed two-stroke diesel engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] They can reach efficiencies of up to 55%.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Unlike most regular diesel engines, two-stroke watercraft engines use highly viscous fuel oil.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The first diesel engines for ships were made by A.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] These engines were three-cylinder units of 120 PS (88 kW) and four-cylinder units of 180 PS (132 kW) and used for Russian ships.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In World War I, especially submarine diesel engine development advanced quickly.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] By the end of the War, double acting piston two-stroke engines with up to 12,200 PS (9 MW) had been made for marine use.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines had been used in aircraft before World War II, for instance, in the rigid airship *LZ 129 Hindenburg,* which was powered by four Daimler-Benz DB 602 diesel engines, or in several Junkers aircraft, which had Jumo 205 engines installed.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In 1929, in the United States, the Packard Motor Company developed America's first aircraft diesel engine, the Packard DR-980—an air-cooled, 9-cylinder radial engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Additional advantages cited, at the time, included a lower risk of post-crash fire, and superior performance at high altitudes.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] On March 6, 1930, the engine received an Approved Type Certificate—first ever for an aircraft diesel engine—from the U.S.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] However, noxious exhaust fumes, cold-start and vibration problems, engine structural failures, the death of its developer, and the industrial economic contraction of the Great Depression, combined to kill the program.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] From then, until the late 1970s, there had not been many applications of the diesel engine in aircraft.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In 1978, Piper Cherokee co-designer Karl H.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] However, with the 1970s energy crisis and environmental movement, and resulting pressures for greater fuel economy, reduced carbon and lead in the atmosphere, and other issues, there was a resurgence of interest in diesel engines for aircraft.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] High-compression piston aircraft engines that run on aviation gasoline ("avgas") generally require the addition of toxic Tetraethyl lead to avgas, to avoid engine pre-ignition and detonation; but diesel engines do not require leaded fuel.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Also, biodiesel can, theoretically, provide a net reduction in atmospheric carbon compared to avgas.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] For these reasons, the general aviation community has begun to fear the possible banning or discontinuance of leaded avgas.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Additionally, avgas is a specialty fuel in very low (and declining) demand, compared to other fuels, and its makers are susceptible to costly aviation-crash lawsuits, reducing refiners' interest in producing it.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Outside the United States, avgas has already become increasingly difficult to find at airports (and generally), than less-expensive, diesel-compatible fuels like Jet-A and other jet fuels.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] By the late 1990s / early 2000s, diesel engines were beginning to appear in light aircraft.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Most notably, Frank Thielert and his Austrian engine enterprise, began developing diesel engines to replace the 100 horsepower (75 kW) - 350 horsepower (260 kW) gasoline/piston engines in common light aircraft use.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] First successful application of the Theilerts to production aircraft was in the Diamond DA42 Twin Star light twin, which exhibited exceptional fuel efficiency surpassing anything in its class, and its single-engined predecessor, the Diamond DA40 Diamond Star.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In subsequent years, several other companies have developed aircraft diesel engines, or have begun to—most notably Continental Aerospace Technologies which, by 2018, was reporting it had sold over 5,000 such engines worldwide.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The United States' Federal Aviation Administration has reported that "by 2007, various jet-fueled piston aircraft had logged well over 600,000 hours of service".
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In recent years (2016), diesel engines have also found use in unmanned aircraft (UAV), due to their reliability, durability, and low fuel consumption.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Non-road diesel engines are commonly used for construction equipment and agricultural machinery.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Fuel efficiency, reliability and ease of maintenance are very important for such engines, whilst high power output and quiet operation are negligible.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Therefore, mechanically controlled fuel injection and air-cooling are still very common.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The common power outputs of non-road diesel engines vary a lot, with the smallest units starting at 3 kW, and the most powerful engines being heavy duty lorry engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Stationary diesel engines are commonly used for electricity generation, but also for powering refrigerator compressors, or other types of compressors or pumps.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Usually, these engines either run continuously with partial load, or intermittently with full load.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Stationary diesel engines powering electric generators that put out an alternating current, usually operate with alternating load, but fixed rotational frequency.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] This is due to the mains' fixed frequency of either 50 Hz (Europe), or 60 Hz (United States).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The engine's crankshaft rotational frequency is chosen so that the mains' frequency is a multiple of it.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] For practical reasons, on typical small generator sets for home use or standby applications (as distinct from continuous operation) this results in crankshaft rotational frequencies of either 25 Hz (1500 per minute) or 30 Hz (1800 per minute).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Larger generator sets, in particular using medium speed engines, operate at synchronous speeds of 500, 514, 600, 720, 750, 900, or 1000 rpm depending on the grid frequency and size of engine.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines with a flexible crankshaft refer to internal combustion engines where the crankshaft exhibits a degree of elasticity due to operational stresses, manufacturing tolerances, and material properties.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Unlike a perfectly rigid crankshaft, a flexible one undergoes dynamic deformations due to cyclic combustion forces, inertial loads, and lubrication effects, which can lead to eccentric motion and vibrational displacement.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] This flexibility can impact engine performance by influencing bearing loads, lubrication film distribution, and mechanical wear, potentially reducing efficiency and lifespan.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Advanced modeling techniques, such as Finite Element Analysis (FEA) and Multi-Body Dynamics (MBD), are used to predict and mitigate these effects, enabling better engine design, improved fuel efficiency, and enhanced durability.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] The flexibility of a crankshaft decreases the mass flow rate of air that goes into cylinders, resulting in an unfavorable higher rate of exhaust emissions like CO.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] A special class of prototype internal combustion piston engines has been developed over several decades with the goal of improving efficiency by reducing heat loss.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] These engines are variously called adiabatic engines (due to better approximation of adiabatic expansion), low heat rejection engines, or high temperature engines.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] They are generally piston engines with combustion chamber parts lined with ceramic thermal barrier coatings.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Some make use of pistons and other parts made of titanium which has a low thermal conductivity and density.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Some designs are able to eliminate the use of a cooling system and associated parasitic losses altogether.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Developing lubricants able to withstand the higher temperatures involved has been a major barrier to commercialization.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] In mid-2010s literature, main development goals for future diesel engines are described as improvements of exhaust emissions, reduction of fuel consumption, and increase of lifespan (2014).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] It is said that the diesel engine, especially the diesel engine for commercial vehicles, will remain the most important vehicle powerplant until the mid-2030s.
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Editors assume that the complexity of the diesel engine will increase further (2014).
[src:diesel-engine/diesel-engine-p02] Some editors expect a future convergency of diesel and Otto engines' operating principles due to Otto engine development steps made towards homogeneous charge compression ignition (2017).
